<h1 class="title">Hsu-Chieh Hu</h1>
</header>
<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>
<p>I am a Ph.D. student in <a href="http://ece.cmu.edu/">Electrical and Computer Engineering Department</a> at <a href="http://cmu.edu/">Carnegie Mellon</a>, currently working on integerating robotics and AI and theirs applications on transportation under the supervision of <a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~sfs/">Stephen F. Smith</a> of  <a href="http://ri.cmu.edu/"> Robotics Institute </a>. </p>



<h2 id="contact">Contact</h2>
<p>My first name at ANDREW dot CMU dot EDU</p>



<h2 id="research">Research</h2>
<ol type="1">
<li>Queue management for Schedule-Driven Traffic Control</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>
A composite approach is proposed to real-time traffic control that uses sensed information on queue lengths to influence scheduling decisions and gracefully shift the signal control strategy to queue management in high volume/high congestion settings. 	
</p>
</blockquote>

<ol start="2" type="1">
<li>Schedule-Driven Demand Shifting</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>We consider a setting where drivers have flexibility in the times that they can arrive and depart from the office, and all drivers must pass through a congestion bottleneck (e.g., a tunnel or a bridge).The goal is to produce a departure time for each driver that minimizes congestion at the bottleneck. </p>
</blockquote>

<ol start="3" type="1">
<li>V-TCP: A New TCP Protocol for Vehicles</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>This project is to design a new TCP protocol for vehicles to support QoS of high throughput transmission.</p>
</blockquote>

